data: {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"toolu_01YC29zNLTqydz39od3xEZ3Q","content":"1) TL;DR: Add type hints. It makes the function\u2019s intent clearer and helps catch misuse earlier with linters/IDEs.\n\n2) Recommended approach (simple path):\n```python\ndef add(a: int | float, b: int | float) -> int | float:\n    return a + b\n```\nEffort: S (<1h)\n\n3) Rationale and trade-offs:  \nType hints improve readability and tooling support without changing behavior. For a tiny function like this, that\u2019s a good low-cost improvement. A docstring or input validation would be unnecessary unless this is part of a public API.\n\n4) Risks and guardrails:  \n- Python won\u2019t enforce types at runtime, so this is mainly for clarity and static analysis.\n- If the function is meant to support more than numbers, use broader types or leave it untyped.\n\n5) When to consider the advanced path:  \nIf this function is exposed to untrusted input or used in a public library, add validation and clearer error handling.\n\n6) Optional advanced path:  \nUse a protocol or generic numeric type if you need stronger typing across many math helpers.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"T-019ce044-a179-7229-8ed6-b39e9b0eaaea"}

